{
  "local_port": 59758,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I deal with extreme confusion, pain & helplessness after being completely cut off by my S.O, who doesn't want any type of contact ever?",
  "response": "I'm so sorry you're going through this. Being cut off by someone you care about deeply can be incredibly painful and disorienting. Here are some steps to help you navigate this difficult time:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Acknowledge Your Emotions**\n- **It\u2019s okay to feel hurt, confused, and helpless.** These emotions are valid and natural in this situation. Allow yourself to feel them without judgment.\n- Journaling can help you process your thoughts and feelings. Writing down what you\u2019re experiencing can be a release and provide clarity.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Create Space for Healing**\n- **Respect their boundaries.** As painful as it is, honoring their request for no contact is crucial for both your healing and theirs.\n- **Limit reminders:** Avoid checking their social media or revisiting places/things that trigger memories. This will help you start to detach emotionally.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Seek Support**\n- **Lean on trusted friends or family.** Share your feelings with people who care about you. You don\u2019t have to go through this alone.\n- **Consider therapy:** A therapist can provide a safe space to process your emotions and help you develop coping strategies.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Focus on Self-Care**\n- **Prioritize your well-being.** Eat nourishing meals, get enough sleep, and engage in physical activity to support your mental health.\n- **Engage in activities that bring you joy or peace**, whether it\u2019s reading, painting, walking in nature, or listening to music.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Reframe Your Perspective**\n- **Remember your worth.** This situation doesn\u2019t define you or your value as a person.\n- **See this as a step toward growth.** While it\u2019s painful, this can be an opportunity to rediscover yourself and what you truly want in life.\n\n---\n\n### **6. Avoid Unhealthy Coping Mechanisms**\n- Resist the urge to numb your pain with alcohol, drugs, or other self-destructive behaviors. These will only prolong your healing.\n\n---\n\n### **7. Give Yourself Time**\n- Healing is not linear. Some days will be harder than others, but gradually, the pain will lessen.\n- Be patient with yourself and trust that, over time, you\u2019ll find clarity and peace.\n\n---\n\n### **8. Consider the Bigger Picture**\n- Reflect on the relationship and the reasons it ended. Were there patterns or behaviors that were unhealthy? This can help you learn and grow for future connections.\n\n---\n\n### **9. Shift Your Focus Forward**\n- Set small, achievable goals for yourself, whether personal, professional, or creative. Focusing on your growth can help you regain a sense of purpose.\n\n---\n\n### **10. Know You\u2019re Not Alone**\n- Many people have experienced similar pain and have come out stronger on the other side. This is a chapter in your life, not the whole story.\n\n---\n\nIf you\u2019re feeling overwhelmed or struggling to cope, please don\u2019t hesitate to reach out to a mental health professional or a support hotline. You deserve care and compassion as you navigate this difficult time. Healing is possible, even if it doesn\u2019t feel that way right now.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
